elements.html:
Welcome to the Mass Casualty Incident Delegation Experiment. Here you will have the chance to review the decisions of other medical professionals in difficult triage scenarios to assess whether you would delegate a triage situation in the future to those decision makers.

The medical professionals whose decisions you will review were triage officers as a part of a 2-man Tactical EMS team that responded to the scene of a subway bombing. The scene was deemed secure prior to the arrival of the team. The triage officer had a triage kit that allowed them to sort and tag victims and, to a limited degree, use tools such as tourniquets to attend to patient injuries.

Each scenario is presented followed by how two different medics carried out their assessment and treatment separately for that situation. Each medic vignette is then followed by a few questions to assess how you perceived the medic’s decision-making style and the way the information was presented.

While you work your way through each vignette Imagine you have seen a lot of other observations of this medic, and the behavior you see here is typical for how they behave.

The survey should take about 15-30 minutes to complete. Thank you for your participation.

elements.decision: How should this patient be treated?
actions: Places a tourniquet on each amputation, three tourniquets in total
elements.explanation: Medic-77 explains that the abdominal wound will need more immediate care including supplies, surgeon and other things. Especially if there are complications. Medic-3 did not choose Patient B or C because Patient B's bleeding was controlled with tourniquet placement and her vitals remained stable while triaging other patients in the scene; Patient C was not chosen because a rapid needle thoracostomy provided near-immediate relief and vital signs stabilized.
